[
  {
    "title": "Measuring Current and Voltage",
    "objective": "Identify the ammeter and voltmeter as the primary tools for measuring current and voltage.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To measure the flow of electricity, we use an ammeter. The ammeter measures current, which is recorded in the SI unit of Amperes (Amps). You can think of current like the flow of water in a pipe; the ammeter counts how much electricity is passing through a specific point in the circuit. Because it measures flow, the ammeter is designed with very low internal resistance so it does not slow down the current it is trying to measure.",
      "To measure electrical pressure or potential difference, we use a voltmeter. The voltmeter measures voltage, which is recorded in the SI unit of Volts (V). While current flows through a component, voltage is measured across two different points to find the difference in pressure between them. A voltmeter has very high internal resistance to ensure it does not draw current away from the circuit. Using an ammeter where a voltmeter is required can cause a short circuit, potentially damaging the meter and the installation."
    ],
    "hint": "Think about whether you are measuring the 'flow' (Amps) or the 'pressure' (Volts) between two points."
  },
  {
    "title": "Measuring Resistance",
    "objective": "Identify the ohmmeter as the instrument for measuring electrical resistance.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Resistance is the opposition to the flow of current within a circuit. We measure this quantity using an ohmmeter. The unit of measurement for resistance is the Ohm, which is represented by the Greek letter Omega (Ω). An ohmmeter works by using its own internal battery to send a tiny, known current through a component to calculate how much that component resists the flow.",
      "Because the ohmmeter provides its own power source, you must only use it on 'dead' circuits—circuits that are completely disconnected from the mains supply. If you attempt to measure resistance on a live circuit, the external voltage will clash with the meter's internal battery. This will result in an inaccurate reading and will likely blow the fuse inside your meter or destroy the instrument's sensitive electronic components. Verifying a circuit is dead before using an ohmmeter is a fundamental safety and equipment-protection rule."
    ],
    "hint": "Remember that resistance (Ohms) measures how much a circuit 'opposes' flow and requires the circuit to be powered off."
  },
  {
    "title": "Measuring Power and Energy",
    "objective": "Distinguish between instruments used for measuring power (Watts) and electrical energy (Joules/kWh).",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Power and energy are closely related, but they require different instruments because they measure different things. Power is the rate at which work is being done at any single moment. We measure power in Watts (W) using a wattmeter. You can compare a wattmeter to a speedometer in a car; it tells you exactly how much 'effort' the electricity is exerting right now.",
      "Electrical energy is the total amount of power used over a specific period of time. The SI unit for energy is the Joule (J), though in the electrical trade, we more commonly use the Kilowatt-hour (kWh). To measure this total consumption, we use an energy meter, often referred to as a kilowatt-hour meter. While the wattmeter shows the instantaneous demand, the energy meter acts like an odometer, recording the cumulative total of energy consumed. An electrician uses a wattmeter to check a machine's performance and an energy meter to determine the total usage for billing or efficiency monitoring."
    ],
    "hint": "One instrument measures the 'rate' of work (Watts), while the other measures the 'total' amount used over time (kWh)."
  },
  {
    "title": "Instrument Selection Logic",
    "objective": "Apply AC2.3 by matching specific electrical quantities to their appropriate measurement instruments.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "Professional competence requires selecting the correct instrument based on the specific SI unit you need to measure. This is known as instrument selection logic. If you are tasked with checking for a broken wire or a 'blown' fuse, you are checking for continuity, which is a measurement of resistance in Ohms (Ω); therefore, you must select an ohmmeter.",
      "If you need to verify if a circuit is live or check the supply level, you are measuring potential difference in Volts (V) and must use a voltmeter. To find out how much load a motor is drawing from the supply, you measure current in Amperes (A) using an ammeter. For measuring the rate of work, use a wattmeter for Watts (W). For the total consumption over time, use an energy meter for Joules (J) or Kilowatt-hours (kWh). Always match the tool to the unit: Amps to Ammeter, Volts to Voltmeter, Ohms to Ohmmeter, Watts to Wattmeter, and Energy to an Energy Meter."
    ],
    "hint": "Always identify the SI unit of the quantity you want to find (Amps, Volts, Ohms, Watts, or Joules) to pick the right tool."
  }
]

